    content:
      'Finding the right art to license for your business is a tough nut to crack. In this article, we have provided an in-depth guide to art licensing which will act as a guiding force for your business. \n\n\n![alt_text](images/image1.jpg "image_tooltip")\n\n\nArtists worldwide get overwhelmed when they discover the field of art licensing. [Licensing](https://www.uschamber.com/co/start/strategy/how-to-license-your-artwork) is an excellent way to earn money by allowing sales of reproduction of your artwork. If you struggle to find the right art to license for your business, then peruse this write-up to get the detailed information regarding art licensing. \n\nTo assist with your quest to find the right art, we have covered a wide array of topics, such as understanding the concept of licensing, the process of licensing, its importance, and its legal and financial aspects. \n\n\n> *“An artist is not paid for his labor but for his vision.” – James Whistler*\n\nEach segment covers relevant information pertaining to art licensing. You can expect to get answers to queries about the meaning, process, agreement, and monetary facet of art licensing.\n\nLet us dive into this guide with the erudite information about art licensing.\n\n\n## How to Find the Right Art to License for Your Business?\n\nFinding the right art to license for a new business might not be as simple as it looks. However, you can start your new venture confidently and succeed with proper knowledge and reliable information.\n\nThe majority of the companies that buy artwork for commercial use have a greater inclination towards something that can be used across a product range. It infers that the artwork should comprise variations on a theme. Basically, this type of art is what defines the licensee requirement. \n\nWhile some would naturally fit, other artists are required to put in the effort to create such artwork with a commercial approach. But before we dig deeper, let us get some clarification on the concept of licensing artwork. \n\n\n## Understanding the Concept of Licensing Artwork\n\nSo, what is art licensing? When artists rent out their artwork (while retaining the copyrights) to other companies for reproduction in a mutually agreed way, it is termed as [licensing artwork](https://www.uschamber.com/co/start/strategy/how-to-license-your-artwork). A legal contract is created to authenticate the terms of the licensing agreement. Therefore, it is basically permission to use the artwork contract.\n\n\n## What Kind of Art Is Good for Licensing?\n\nAny art created by graphics artists or visual artists is good for licensing, and it includes digital art licensing and fine art licensing. \n\nLicensed artwork is mostly used in products such as greeting cards, cups, pillows, blankets, homeware, toys for kids, stationery items, gifts, wallpapers, etc. \n\n\n> *“Art evokes the mystery without which the world would not exist.” – Rene Magritte*\n\nWhile creating the artwork, the prime focus should be on creating work as a set or series. The major advantage of doing so is that your artwork can now be easily translated into a full product range. Selling them as one-off products would be difficult. \n\nConsider artwork on wallpapers, fabric printing, or stationery. The pattern of the artwork is repetitive in such domains. Such artwork would be the right art for licensing. \n\nYou may use any medium for licensed artwork; however, it is important that you use high-resolution scanned images for licensee use.\n\nAnother important notion is the fact that companies prefer using the latest and trendy artwork. Therefore, you need to ensure that your art is up to date with modern trends and style. Approaching them with something that matches their expectation is what this business is all about. \n\n\n## Is Licensing art worthwhile?\n\nNow, this is a tricky one, and the answer honestly depends on what you are looking for. If you are looking for a steady monthly prime source of income, then probably licensing is not a good place to start. First, the royalty or commission payments from licensing are generally paid quarterly. Second, it takes time to build that level of client-base. \n\n\n> *“One of the nice things about licensing music to movies or advertisements is you can reach a lot of people who normally wouldn\'t hear music.” - Moby*\n\nThat being said, the earning potential in the licensing business is tremendous. The royalty income can go as high as millions of dollars annually. However, it would be wise to get into licensing business if you already have a major source of income and are willing to put in the time and effort to grow this source of income gradually. \n\n\n## How to Get Art Licensed?\n\n\n![alt_text](images/image2.jpg "image_tooltip")\n\n\nGetting an art license comes under a legal framework, and it is done by creating an art licensing agreement. \n\nIf you are wondering, “What is an art licensing agreement?”, then let us explain. It is a legally structured document with various details about the art, its use, time frame, and all the other agreed terms and conditions related to the contract. The artwork is licensed once the licensor and the licensee sign this agreement.\n\nThe licensee and licensor can get into the agreement on their own or use art licensing companies\' services. These companies know how to license artwork and can make the process easier.\n\nGetting an art license is a comprehensive process, and, naturally, you might have numerous questions and thoughts about it. If you would like to know more, then check out [this article.](https://startupresource.center/review/the-ultimate-beginners-guide-to-art-licensing) It covers various aspects of artwork licensing agreement, like how to understand art licensing contracts, and also offers tips to get an artwork license agreement template.\n\n\n## The Financial Aspect\n\n\n![alt_text](images/image3.jpg "image_tooltip")\n\n\nWe have yet to discuss the monetary aspect of art licensing. You must still be curious to get answers to questions such as:\n\n\n\n* What is a typical licensing fee?\n* How much does art licensing cost?\n* How are royalties paid to artists?\n\nTypically, the licensing fee for artwork can be either fixed or percentage base. The licensing fee or the royalty varies from product to product. You may want to check the industry average for your product to negotiate a realistic fee figure. \n\nGetting a licensing contract done from a lawyer may cost somewhere between the range of $100-$500 depending on the hours they put in. However, many online resources offer art licensing agreement templates at a fixed cost ranging from $50 to $100. But if you are looking for something drafted [as per your needs](https://startupresource.center/review/small-business-startup-law-firm-invest-in-counsel-that-fits-your-needs), the cost may go as high as $1200. \n\n\n## Royalty and Commissions\n\nThere are certainly major differences between royalty and commissions. [Royalties](https://researchpedia.info/difference-between-royalties-and-commissions/) are offered on intellectual property such as art. The company pays a specific percentage of sale or profit to the copyright holder on an ongoing basis against the right to use their intellectual property for commercial use. Whereas commission is paid as a one-time payment against a sale or profit. \n\n\n## Final Thoughts\n\nFinding the right art to license for your business may become a daunting task if you start without the correct information. Hopefully, this write-up helped you gain valuable insight into art licensing. If you have any queries or need any assistance with your art licensing business, then get in touch with [Angel Scale](https://startupresource.center/) today.',
